    "captions": {
        "voice_rules": [
            "Keep it friendly, simple, and upbeat. Short sentences. No corporate or salesy language.",
            "Lead with the experience and the feeling (easy day outside, time with friends/family, quiet water) before mentioning the rental itself.",
            "Use local framing: Woodbridge, Northern Virginia, the Potomac River, Neabsco Creek, Hampton's Landing Marina.",
            "Prioritize fishing and recreational boating content. Periodically rotate in secondary audiences (bachelor/bachelorette parties, birthdays, corporate outings, team-building, group trips).",
            "Actively encourage WEEKDAY trips. Frame weekdays as quieter water, easier launches, and a calmer experience. Driving weekday demand is a core goal.",
            "For pontoon rentals, CTAs may direct to the website to reserve/book.",
            "For kayak and paddleboard rentals, do NOT say 'reserve' or 'book now'. These are first come, first served with no reservation needed. Say 'just show up' and note that large groups should call ahead.",
            "Name real destinations when relevant: Neabsco Creek, Leesylvania State Park, Julie J. Metz Wetlands Preserve, Featherstone National Wildlife Refuge.",
            "Respect the season: Potomac Boat Rentals operates roughly April through early November. Do not promote rentals as available in the off-season.",
            "Never use an em dash or a double hyphen (— or --) anywhere in a caption. Use a period, comma, or colon instead.",
            "Hashtags: treat the hashtags list as a pool, not a fixed block. Pick up to 6 per post that actually match the post's content, mixing 2-3 brand/local tags (#PotomacBoatRentals, #Woodbridge, #NeabscoCreek) with 2-3 broad-reach tags (#BoatLife, #Fishing, #Kayaking, #GetOutside). A fishing post gets #BassFishing, not #Paddleboarding."
        ],
        "compliance": {
            "avoid": [
                "corporate or stiff B2B language",
                "promising specific fish catches or guaranteed wildlife sightings",
                "telling people to 'reserve' or 'book' kayaks or paddleboards (those are first come, first served)",
