    "images": {
        "visual_style": {
            "industry_plain": "boat, kayak, and paddleboard rental business on the Potomac River and Neabsco Creek in Woodbridge, Virginia, with pontoons, kayaks, and stand-up paddleboards on the water",
            "scene_guidance": "Generate a unique, specific one-line scene description for EACH post, framed as a candid photo someone actually took on their phone that day, never a staged or cinematic shot. Vary across: SETTING (open Potomac River, calm Neabsco Creek, marina dock at Hampton's Landing, wetlands shoreline, near Leesylvania State Park, a quiet cove, the launch ramp), TIME OF DAY (early morning calm, golden-hour sun, bright midday, warm late afternoon, sunset on the water), SUBJECT (a family on a pontoon, a couple paddling a double kayak, friends laughing on a pontoon, a solo angler fishing from a jon boat, a paddleboarder gliding through still water, kayaks lined up at the dock, a group loading up for the day), CAMERA ANGLE (mid-distance group shot on the pontoon with water and shoreline around them, wide shot from the dock with the marina in frame, over-the-shoulder from the boat, low angle from water level, close-up on hands paddling or a fishing rod, candid mid-laugh group shot from a few feet back, occasional arm's-length selfie). PEOPLE RULE: any person must be clearly visible, in focus, and well lit at a natural mid-range distance: near enough that the face has real definition (never blurred, melted, or featureless, even at a distance), far enough that the person never fills the frame. Prefer environment-rich compositions over portraits; tight close-up face portraits are the fastest way to look AI-generated and are banned, as are people rendered as tiny distant specks. PLACE ANCHORS: ground most scenes in a recognizable piece of the real business when the setting allows: weathered dock boards, the Hampton's Landing marina docks in the background, Potomac Boat Rentals signage or the branded pontoon panel, a branded staff shirt, the colorful kayak rack. PEOPLE STYLE: natural-looking, slightly fit adults (never overly muscular, unusually athletic, or obese); in group scenes keep roughly a 2:1 female-to-male ratio; summer clothing that says warm weather (t-shirts, tank tops, shorts, sundresses, caps, sunglasses); expressions are relaxed easy smiles, mid-conversation warmth, or quiet contentment, NEVER exaggerated open-mouth laughing (synchronized big laughs read robotic). LIFE JACKETS: people do not wear them; instead show bright orange life jackets stowed naturally somewhere on the boat (draped over a rail, resting on a seat, hung near the helm). SUMMER RULE: every scene must read unmistakably as high summer: lush green foliage and marsh grass, warm light, summer clothing; the marina and water should feel alive and welcoming (other boats, gear, background activity), never empty or abandoned. Morning mist and golden-hour backlight are welcome atmosphere; soft overcast is allowed only if the scene still feels warm, green, and inviting. Never repeat the same setting + subject + angle combination across the last 5 posts.",
            "scenes_to_avoid": "no rough or stormy water, no obviously AI-generated or plastic-looking people, no airbrushed or poreless skin, no tight close-up face portraits (the person must never fill the frame), no exaggerated open-mouth laughing on every face, no people wearing life jackets (stow them visibly on the boat instead), no cinematic or stock-photo color grading, no perfectly symmetrical or overly composed shots, no tiny distant or blurred people as the main subject, no winter or off-season scenes, no brown dead marsh grass or bare trees, no abandoned-looking empty marina, no crowded party-boat chaos, no oversaturated artificial colors",
            "color_palette": "natural sunny outdoor colors exactly as a phone camera would capture them: blue water, green shoreline, warm sunlight, clear skies; true to life, never oversaturated or filter-looking",
            "mood_modifier": "relaxed, fun, and easy, the feeling of an effortless local day outside on the water; hyper-realistic candid smartphone-photo quality with the small imperfections of a real photo: natural skin texture, mild phone-camera lens distortion, slight grain, a not-quite-level horizon, casual imperfect framing, and atmospheric depth as the main realism signal: low morning mist on the water, golden-hour backlight with a blown-out sun and lens flare, or soft overcast flatness, the way a friend's photo from a day on the river actually looks"
        },
